# HIV Host Response — Persistent Immune Activation

## Background
Even in virologically suppressed HIV+ individuals on ART, 
chronic immune activation persists — driving non-AIDS 
comorbidities including cardiovascular disease, 
neurodegeneration, and accelerated aging phenotypes. 
The transcriptional basis of this persistent activation 
remains incompletely understood.

## Objective
To characterize host transcriptional response in HIV+ 
individuals using bulk RNA-seq DEG analysis, with a focus 
on persistent immune activation signatures — interferon 
signaling, NF-κB activation, and T cell exhaustion.

## Methods
- Bulk RNA-seq data from public GEO datasets
- DEG analysis using DESeq2 in R
- PPI network construction via STRINGdb + Cytoscape
- Pathway enrichment via clusterProfiler (KEGG, Reactome, GO)
- Hub gene identification using CytoHubba

## Expected Key Pathways
- Interferon stimulated genes (ISGs)
- NF-κB signaling
- T cell exhaustion markers (PD-1, TIM-3, LAG-3)
- Inflammasome activation (NLRP3)
- TNF and IL-6 signaling

